                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>Richmond</placeName>
                                        <date>January 14<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1849</date>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">
                                        <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(3)">Dear Friend</p>
                              <p rend="indent(5)">Doubtlessly long since<lb/> you have given up all
                                        idea of receiving a reply to yours, when<lb/> I received in
                                        due time, &amp; would apologize to you, if I knew<lb/> what
                                        excuse to make, but to you I need but <sic>acknoledge</sic>
                                        my<lb/> remissness &amp; I know you will excuse me, although
                                        I have in<lb/> part some slight excuse to offer, that is my
                                        business anxieties<lb/> have engrossed the whole of my
                                        attention, so that neither <persName>Mr.<lb/> S.
                                                  Heyman</persName> or myself have had sufficient
                                        unoccupied time<lb/> to attend to your matters here. Our
                                        congregation matters are<lb/> at a very low ebb, in
                                        consequence of not sufficient energy<lb/> in all of its
                                        members. I almost feel that we can never thrive<lb/> again,
                                        many of our members are going over to the other
                                        Congre-<lb/>-gation &amp; for the two last Sabbaths, we have
                                        not had<lb/> Minyan in Shool Until we get a good Hazan, one
                                        who<lb/> is in every way competent to inspire us with
                                        religious feeling<lb/> &amp; one whom we can respect &amp;
                                        look up to for instruction, we<lb/> must continue to
                                        decrease.</p>
                              <p>I must again say that if you had an enterprising agent<lb/> here,
                                        that a good deal could be done with your various works<lb/>
                                        &amp; really I do not know whom to advise you to appoint, as<lb/>
                                        <persName>Mr. S. Hyman</persName> will leave
                                                  <placeName>Richmond</placeName> in a few weeks
                                        to<lb/> enter business in <placeName>Petersburg</placeName>
                                        with <persName>Michael Davis</persName>, son of<lb/>
                                        <persName>Goodman Davis</persName>, consequently you cannot
                                        obtain his<lb/> services. As regards the Jewish Publication
                                        Society, that</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>with all other religious matters as I before remarked, are, at<lb/>
                                        a very low Ebb, there has not been a meeting of that
                                        Society<lb/> for more than a year and half; all &amp; every
                                        thing is in a very<lb/> deplorable state In looking over
                                        list of your Delinquents I am<lb/> sorry to inform you that
                                        many of your Claims you will<lb/> not realize one Cent from,
                                        as regards the among against<lb/> me, I have always
                                        understood that <persName>Jacob Ezekiel</persName> gave
                                        me<lb/> credit for the amount, this is the case with many
                                        others to<lb/> whom <persName>Ezekiel's</persName> hands
                                        until you can get an agent, for as<lb/> long as they remain
                                        in his possession, you must necessarily<lb/> loose. We are
                                        all Thank God in usual Health, excepting<lb/> Father, who is
                                        suffering from scalded feet</p>
                              <p>Wishing you Health Prosperity</p>
                              <p rend="indent(5)">I remain</p>
                              <p rend="indent(5)">your Friend</p>
                              <p rend="indent(5)">
                                        <persName role="author">Isaac A Levy</persName>
                              </p>
                              <p><persName>Mrs. Levy</persName> desires her regards.</p>
                              <p>P.S. Since writing the above, I have conversed with
                                                  <persName>Mr.<lb/> N. Ezekiel</persName>, who is
                                        willing to undertake the agency.</p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p>
                                        <placeName>371 Walnut Street</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">
                                        <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
                              </p>
